{{Dynamic list}} [[File:Thomas Arthur Garner.jpg|thumb|Thomas Arthur Garner (abt. 1945)]] This is a list of incidents attributed in popular culture to the '''[[Bermuda Triangle]] Or Devil's Triangle'''
== Aircraft incidents == * 1945: July 10, Thomas Arthur Garner, AMM3, USN, along with eleven other crew members, was lost at sea in a US Navy PBM3S patrol seaplane, Bu. No.6545, Sqd VPB2-OTU#3, in the Bermuda Triangle. They left the [[Patrick Air Force Base|Naval Air Station, Banana River, Florida]], at 7:07 p.m. on July 9, 1945, for a radar training flight to [[Great Exuma]], Bahamas. Their last radio position report was sent at 1:16 a.m., July 10, 1945, with a latitude/longitude of 25-22N 77.34W, near Providence Island, after which they were never heard from again. An extensive ten day surface and air search, including a carrier sweep, found nothing.<ref>Garner family records. Further information available upon request from dgarner@PacBell.net</ref> * 1945: December 5, [[Flight 19]] (five [[Grumman TBF Avenger|TBF Avenger]]s) lost with 14 airmen, and later the same day [[Martin PBM Mariner|PBM Mariner]] BuNo 59225 lost with 13 airmen while searching for Flight 19.<ref>[http://www.history.navy.mil/faqs/faq15-1.htm Flight 19] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413074152/http://www.history.navy.mil/faqs/faq15-1.htm|date=2009-04-13}} Department of the Navy, Naval Historical Center – The Loss Of Flight 19</ref> * 1947: July 3, According to the Bermuda Triangle Legend a [[Boeing B-29 Superfortress|B-29 Superfortress]] was lost off Bermuda. Lawrence Kunsche investigated and found no reference to any such B-29 loss. In fact the aircraft loss was that of a [[Douglas C-54 Skymaster|Douglas C-54]] which was lost in a storm off the Florida coast <ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19470703-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Douglas C-54G-1-DO Skymaster 45-519 Florida coast, USA|author=Harro Ranter|date=3 July 1947|publisher=}}</ref> A B-29 ''was'' lost in the vicinity of Bermuda;-on November 16, 1949 a B-29 was lost in the Atlantic; 2 crewmen were missing but on November 19, 1949, 18 survivors were rescued 385 miles northeast of Bermuda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19491120&id=Dc0wAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0Q0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6328,2321471&hl=en|title=The Milwaukee Sentinel November 20, 1949|website=google.com|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> * 1948: January 30, [[Avro Tudor]] [[G-AHNP "Star Tiger"|G-AHNP ''Star Tiger'']] lost with six crew and 25 passengers, en route from [[Santa Maria Airport (Azores)|Santa Maria Airport]] in the [[Azores]] to [[Kindley Air Force Base|Kindley Field]], [[Bermuda]].<ref>[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19480130-0 G-AHNP] Aviation Safety Network – Avro 688 Tudor 1 G-AHNP</ref> * 1948: December 28, [[Douglas DC-3]] [[NC16002 disappearance|NC16002]] lost with three crew and 36 passengers, en route from [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], to [[Miami]], Florida.<ref>[http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19481228-0 NC16002] Aviation Safety Network – Douglas DC-3DST-144 NC16002</ref> * 1949: January 17, Avro Tudor [[G-AGRE "Star Ariel"|G-AGRE ''Star Ariel'']] lost with seven crew and 13 passengers, en route from [[Kindley Air Force Base|Kindley Field]], [[Bermuda]], to [[Norman Manley International Airport|Kingston Airport]], [[Jamaica]].<ref>[http://1000aircraftphotos.com/Contributions/Coates/1422.htm G-AGRE] Avro 688 Tudor Mk.1 G-AGRE c/n 1253 – Jack McKillop</ref> * 1956: November 9, Martin Marlin lost ten crewmen taking off from Bermuda. * 1962: January 8, A USAF [[Boeing B-50 Superfortress|KB-50]] 51-0465 was lost over the Atlantic between the US East Coast and the Azores<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=74687|title=ASN Aircraft accident 08-JAN-1962 Boeing KB-50K Superfortress 51-0465|author=Harro Ranter|publisher=}}</ref> * 1965: June 9, A USAF C-119 Flying Boxcar of the [[440th Airlift Wing|440th Troop Carrier Wing]] missing between Florida and [[Grand Turk Island]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19650605-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Fairchild C-119G Flying Boxcar 51-2680 Crooked Island, Bahamas|first=Harro|last=Ranter|website=aviation-safety.net|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> The last call from the plane came from a point just north of [[Crooked Island, Bahamas]], and 177 miles from Grand Turk Island. On July 18, 1965 debris from the plane was found on the beach of Gold Rock Cay just off the northeastern shore of [[Acklins Island]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1499&dat=19650811&id=PVYaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ricEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4417,172414&hl=en|title=The Milwaukee Journal August 11, 1965|website=google.com|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> * 1965: December 6, Private ERCoupe F01<ref>[The Legend lists plane loss as a "Cessna" But see NTSA report]</ref> lost with pilot and one passenger, en route from Ft. Lauderdale to Grand Bahamas Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/_layouts/ntsb.aviation/brief.aspx?ev_id=72540&key=0|title=NTSB Record as NTSB Identification: MIA66A0065|website=ntsb.gov|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> * 2005: June 20, A Piper-PA-23 disappeared between [[Treasure Cay]] Island, Bahamas and [[Fort Pierce, Florida]]. There were three people on board.<ref name="recent">{{cite web |url=http://paranormal.lovetoknow.com/Recent_Disappearances_in_the_Bermuda_Triangle |title=Recent Disappearances in the Bermuda Triangle |work=lovetoknow.com |accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref> * 2007: April 10, A Piper PA-46-310P disappeared near Berry Island after flying into a level 6 thunderstorm and losing altitude. Two fatalities were listed.<ref>{{cite web|title=ASN Wikibase Occurrence # 43829|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=43829}}</ref> * 2017: February 23, The Turkish Airlines flight TK183 (an Airbus A330-200) was forced to change its direction from Havana, Cuba to Washington Dulles airport after some mechanical and electrical problems occurred over the triangle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/kubaya-giden-thy-ucagi-abdye-zorunlu-inis-yapti-40375567|title=The Turkish Airlines plane en route to Cuba landed to the US}}</ref> * 2017: May 15, A private [[Mitsubishi MU-2|MU-2B]] aircraft was at 24,000 feet when it vanished from radar and radio contact with air traffic controllers in Miami.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2017/05/16/small-plane-carrying-four-new-yorkers-goes-missing-near-bahamas/|title=Small plane carrying family vanishes in Bermuda Triangle|last=Li|first=David K.|last2=Sheehy|first2=Kate|date=2017-05-16|website=New York Post|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> Plane wreckage was found.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=195420|title=ASN Aircraft 15-MAY-2017 Mitsubishi MU-2B-40 N220N|first=Harro|last=Ranter|website=aviation-safety.net|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref>
==Incidents at sea == *1492: on the night of October 11, Christopher Columbus and the crew of the Santa Maria reported a sighting of unknown light, just days before the landing at Guanahani.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.millersville.edu/~columbus/data/art/MARVEL01.ART |title=Columbus: The Light of 11 October, 1492 |publisher=The Islands' Sun |date=March–April 1990 |accessdate=2010-05-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907085314/http://www.millersville.edu/~columbus/data/art/MARVEL01.ART |archivedate=September 7, 2008 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> *1800: {{USS|Pickering|1798|6}}, on course from Guadeloupe to Delaware, lost with 90 people on board.<ref name=Berlitz77>Berlitz, Charles, and J. Manson Valentine. Without a Trace. Garden City, N.Y.: Doubleday, 1977. Print.</ref> {Possibly lost in a gale} *1812: ''Patriot'' on her way from Charleston, South Carolina to New York City on December 30, 1812. [[Theodosia Burr Alston]], daughter of [[Aaron Burr]], was lost with her<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/aaron-burr-9232241|title=Aaron Burr|website=Biography.com|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref>{Possibly lost in a storm} *1814: {{USS|Wasp|1814|6}}, last known position was the Caribbean, lost with 140 people on board.<ref name=Berlitz77/> {Possibly lost in a storm} *1824: {{USS|Wild Cat|1822|6}}, on course from Cuba to Tompkins Island, lost with 14 people on board.<ref name=Berlitz77/> {Note lost in a Gale with 31 on board} *1840: ''Rosalie'', found abandoned except for a canary.<ref name=Berlitz77/> {Possibly the "Rossini" found derelict{?}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bermuda-triangle.org/html/the_derelict_rosalie.html |title=The derelict Rosalie |work=www.bermuda-triangle.org |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305030805/http://www.bermuda-triangle.org/html/the_derelict_rosalie.html |archivedate=March 5, 2016 }}</ref> * 1881: According to Legend a sailing ship the "[[Ellen Austin]]" found a derelict vessel and placed a crew to sail the vessel to port. Two versions of what happened to the vessel are: the vessel was either lost in a storm or was found again without a crew. Lawrence David Kusche author of "The Bermuda Triangle Mystery-Solved" found no mention in 1880 or 1881 newspapers of this alleged incident-he did trace the legend to a book by Rupert Gould "The Stargazer Talks" published in 1943. The "Ellen Austin" did exist; a check from Lloyd's of London records proved the existence of Meta, built in 1854, and that in 1880, Meta was renamed Ellen Austin. There are no casualty listings for this vessel, or any vessel at that time, that would suggest a large number of missing men were placed on board a derelict that later disappeared although one website includes the alleged derelict vessel incident it does find that Rupert Gould talked about the legend on radio in the 1930s<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sometimes-interesting.com/2015/12/10/the-ellen-austin-encounter/|title=The Ellen Austin Encounter|last=Sometimes Interesting|date=2015-12-10|website=Sometimes Interesting|accessdate=2017-07-17}}</ref>; likewise the website traces the derelict story to a June 1906 newspaper story-which claims the derelict ship incident took place in 1891-<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sometimes-interesting.com/2015/12/10/the-ellen-austin-encounter/|title=The Ellen Austin Encounter|last=Sometimes Interesting|date=2015-12-10|website=Sometimes Interesting|accessdate=2017-07-17}}</ref>however the 1906 story does not give a reference of where this story came from! * 1918: {{USS|Cyclops|AC-4|6}}, collier, left [[Barbados]] on March 4, lost with all 306 crew and passengers en route to [[Baltimore, Maryland]].<ref>[http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c/cyclops.htm USS Cyclops] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100810203810/http://www.history.navy.mil/danfs/c/cyclops.htm|date=2010-08-10}} Department of the Navy, Naval Historical Center – Dictionary of American Naval Fighting Ships</ref> * 1921: January 31, ''[[Carroll A. Deering]]'', five-masted schooner, Captain W. B. Wormell, found aground and abandoned at Diamond Shoals, near Cape Hatteras, North Carolina.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9JuNcIrkjx8C|title=Ghost Ship of Diamond Shoals|last=Simpson|first=Bland|publisher=UNC Press Books|date=2005}}</ref> * 1925: 1 December, {{SS|Cotopaxi}}, having departed [[Charleston, South Carolina]] two days earlier bound for [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], radioed a [[Distress signal|distress call]] reporting that the ship was sinking. She was officially listed as overdue on 31 December.<ref name=Times311225>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Mails and Shipping |day_of_week=Thursday |date=31 December 1925 |page_number=18 |issue=44157 |column=D}}</ref> * 1941: {{USS|Proteus|AC-9}}, lost with all 58 persons on board in heavy seas, having departed [[Saint Thomas, U.S. Virgin Islands|St. Thomas]] in the [[Virgin Islands]] with a cargo of bauxite on 23 November. The following month, her sister ship {{USS|Nereus|AC-10}} was lost with all 61 persons on board, having also departed St. Thomas with a cargo of bauxite, on 10 December. According to research by Rear Admiral George van Deurs, USN, who was familiar with this type of ship from their service in the USN, the acidic coal cargo would seriously erode the longitudinal support beams, making these aging and poorly constructed colliers extremely vulnerable to breaking up in heavy seas.<ref name="familyheritage">{{cite web|url=http://familyheritage.ca/Articles/merchant1.html|title=Naval History.ca – History of the Royal Canadian Navy – Canadian Merchant Ship Losses, 1939–1945|author=Rob Fisher|publisher=}}</ref> They were both sister ships of the USS Cyclops. * 1958: ''Revonoc''.A 43 foot racing yawl was lost with owner Harvey Conover and four others between Key West and Miami Florida in a hurricane. The only trace found was the Revonoc 14 foot skiff near Jupiter Florida<ref>[https://www.si.com/vault/1958/01/20/570455/nature-keeps-a-grim-date-at-sea Nature Keeps a Grim Date at sea Sports Illustrated January 20,1958 Archive accessed September 29,2018]</ref> * 1963: {{SS|Marine Sulphur Queen}}, lost with 39 crewmen, having departed [[Beaumont, Texas]], on 2 February with a cargo of 15,260 tons of sulphur. She was last heard from on 4 February, when she was in rough, nearly following seas of 16 feet, with northerly winds of 25–46 knots, and listed as missing two days later. The Coast Guard subsequently determined that the ship was unsafe and not seaworthy, and never should have sailed. The final report suggested four causes of the disaster, all due to poor design and maintenance of the ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.pacbell.net/corwind/cgreport.html|title=Marine Sulphur Queen Coast Guard Report Summary of Findings|website=pacbell.net|accessdate=15 July 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509103209/http://home.pacbell.net/corwind/cgreport.html|archivedate=9 May 2008|df=}}</ref> * 2015: In late July, 2015, two 14-year-old boys, Austin Stephanos and Perry Cohen went on a fishing trip in their 19-foot boat. Despite the 15,000 square nautical mile wide search by [[US Coast Guard]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://madmikesamerica.com/2015/07/2-boys-in-a-fishing-boat-vanish-in-the-bermuda-triangle/|title=2 Boys in a Fishing Boat Vanish In the Bermuda Triangle|date=26 July 2015|website=madmikesamerica.com|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> the pair's boat was found a year later off the coast of [[Bermuda]], but the boys were never seen again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cbs12.com/news/local/one-year-later-austin-perry-boat-found|title=ONE YEAR LATER: Austin & Perry Boat Found|first=Greg|last=Angel|website=cbs12.com|accessdate=15 July 2017}}</ref> * 2015: {{SS|El Faro}} sank off of the coast of the Bahamas within the triangle on October 1, 2015. Search crews identified the vessel 15,000 feet below the surface.
== Incidents on land == *1969: [[Great Isaac Lighthouse]] ([[Bimini]], [[Bahamas]]) – Two keepers disappeared and were never found.<ref>{{cite rowlett|bhs}}</ref> (A hurricane passed through at the time of the disappearances).
