[[Image:Parma-teatro-farnese-in-national-gallery.jpg|thumb|220px|Teatro Farnese in [[Parma]]]] '''Teatro Farnese''' is a [[Baroque]]-style [[Theater (structure)|theatre]] in the [[Palazzo della Pilotta]], [[Parma]], [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite book| first=Paolo| last=Landriani| year=1830| title=''Storia e Descrizione de' Principali Teatri Antichi e Moderni''| editor = Dottore Giulio Ferrario | pages=142–150 | publisher=Tipografia del Dottor Giulio Ferrario, Contrada del Bocchetto N. 2465|id= |url=http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/004309091| authorlink=}}</ref> It was built in 1618 by [[Giovanni Battista Aleotti]]. The idea of creating this great theater comes from the Duke of Parma and Piacenza [[Ranuccio I Farnese, Duke of Parma|Ranuccio I Farnese]]. The theatre was almost destroyed by an [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] [[strategic bombing|air raid]] during World War II (1944). It was rebuilt and reopened in 1962.
Some claim this as the first permanent [[proscenium]] theatre (that is, a theatre in which the audience views the action through a single frame, which is known as the "proscenium arch").<ref>King, p. 550</ref><ref>Kuritz, p. 167</ref>
