{{Infobox person |name = Vladislav Anatolievich Horohorin |image = |image_size = |caption = |native_name = Владислав Анатольевич Хорохорин |birth_name = |birth_date = {{birth year and age|1982}} |birth_place = |residence = Moscow, Russia |nationality = Israeli, Russian |other_names = BadB (hacker [[User (computing)|handle]]) |citizenship = Israeli, Russian |known_for = [[hacker (computer security)|Hacking]] | home_town = Donetsk, Ukraine | criminal_charge = Wire fraud |ethnicity = }}
'''Vladislav Anatolievich Horohorin''', ({{lang-ru|Владислав Анатольевич Хорохорин}}), alias '''BadB''', is a former [[hacker]] and international [[Carding (fraud)|credit card trafficker]] who was convicted<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/international-credit-card-trafficker-sentenced-88-months-prison|title=International Credit Card Trafficker Sentenced to 88 Months in Prison|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> of wire fraud and served a seven-year prison sentence.
== Early life == Horohorin was born on September 29, 1982, and grew up in [[Donetsk|Donetsk, Ukraine]], emigrating in 1999 to Israel with his mother, where he served in the [[Israel Defense Forces|Israeli Defence Forces]].
== Investigation == According to the undercover investigation led by the [[United States Secret Service]], Horohorin was one of the founders of [[CarderPlanet]], one of several websites taken down<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.wired.com/science/discoveries/news/2007/02/72585?currentPage=all|title=Crime Boards Come Crashing Down|last=Wired|website=WIRED|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> in 2004 as part of the Secret Service's [[Operation Firewall]] investigation. The web sites were operated by [[cyber criminal]] organizations to [[Carding (fraud)|traffic counterfeit credit cards]], and false identification information and documents. These websites not only shared information on how to commit fraud, but also provided a forum through which to purchase fraud-related information and tools. "The network created by the founders of CarderPlanet, including Vladislav Horohorin, remains one of the most sophisticated organizations of online financial criminals in the world," said Michael Merritt, Assistant Director for Investigations. "This network has been repeatedly linked to nearly every major intrusion of financial information reported to the international law enforcement community. This arrest illustrates the significance of the Secret Service's commitment to traversing the globe in pursuit of online criminals."{{cn|date=January 2018}}
Horohorin promoted his illegal activities by creating video cartoons ridiculing American card holders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/08/badb/|title=Alleged Carder 'BadB' Busted in France — Watch His Cartoon|last=Zetter|first=Kim|work=WIRED|access-date=2017-10-26|language=en-US}}</ref>
Separately, in 2013, Horohorin was named co-conspirator in an indictment, but was not subsequently charged, in a criminal case in District of New Jersey 09-626(JBS), in which other Russian individuals were charged with successfully hacking Nasdaq, 7-Eleven, Carefour, JCPenney, Heartland Payment Systems, Dow Jones, Jetblue and 23 more corporations.<ref>http://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/drinkman072513.pdf</ref><ref>https://www.justice.gov/usao-nj/pr/five-indicted-new-jersey-largest-known-data-breach-conspiracy</ref> This breach was called the "Largest known data breach conspiracy ever prosecuted" by the U.S. Justice Department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/russian-national-admits-role-largest-known-data-breach-conspiracy-ever-prosecuted|title=Russian National Admits Role in Largest Known Data Breach Conspiracy Ever Prosecuted|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> As of April 2017, none of Horohorin's co-conspirators had been sentenced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/a/russian-hacker-drinkman-guilty-fraud/27250304.html|title=Russian Pleads Guilty In Hacking Case|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/russian-national-admits-role-largest-known-data-breach-conspiracy-ever-prosecuted|title=Russian National Admits Role in Largest Known Data Breach Conspiracy Ever Prosecuted|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref>
== Arrest, extradition, guilty plea, and sentencing == Horohorin was identified as "BadB" in November 2009 in a sealed indictment from the United States attorney's office.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:bC9KS1UCBtcJ:https://www.wired.com/images_blogs/threatlevel/2010/08/BadB-Indictment-in-DC.pdf|title=UNITED STATES DISTRICT COURT|last=Helms|first=Fred|website=webcache.googleusercontent.com|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref> He was arrested on August 7, 2010, in Nice, France, while attempting to board an airplane to Warsaw, Poland.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/08/11/AR2010081105791.html|title=French arrest cyber-crime suspect for U.S.|last=Hsu|first=Spencer S.|date=2010-08-12|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1302413/Vladislav-Horohorin-One-worlds-wanted-cyber-criminals-caught-Riviera.html|title=One of 'world's most wanted cyber criminals' caught on French Riviera|work=Mail Online|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.finextra.com/newsarticle/21692/russian-carder-arrested-in-france|title=Russian carder arrested in France|date=2010-08-12|website=Finextra Research|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3934789,00.html|title=Israeli 'credit card trafficker' arrested in France|work=Ynetnews|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Justice/2010/0811/Alleged-global-credit-card-fraud-kingpin-arrested-in-France|title=Alleged global credit card fraud kingpin arrested in France|last=Richey|first=Warren|date=2010-08-11|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2017-04-24|issn=0882-7729}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/7941148/One-of-worlds-most-wanted-cyber-criminals-arrested.html|title=One of 'world's most wanted cyber-criminals' arrested|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/CRIME/08/11/credit.card.trafficking.arrest/|title=Alleged credit card trafficker arrested in France - CNN.com|last=Staff|first=By the CNN Wire|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmagazine.com/arrested-seller-of-card-data-to-be-extradited-to-us/article/558028/|title=Arrested seller of card data to be extradited to U.S.|date=2010-08-12|work=SC Magazine US|access-date=2017-04-24|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2010/08/badb/|title=Alleged Carder 'BadB' Busted in France — Watch His Cartoon|last=Zetter|first=Kim|work=WIRED|access-date=2017-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref> However, due to the complexity of the international legal battle that followed his arrest, he was not extradited to the United States until June 6, 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.prleap.com/pr/187142/carderplanet-founder-vladislav-horohorin-is|title=CarderPlanet Founder Vladislav Horohorin is Extradited to the United States|work=PR Leap|access-date=2017-09-09|language=en}}</ref> During the proceedings in France, Horohorin was incarcerated in the Maison D'Arret D'Aix-Luynes near Aix-en-Provence, France.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/2011/09/21/01016-20110921ARTFIG00350-le-roi-des-hackers-bientot-extrade-vers-les-etats-unis.php|title=Le roi des hackers bientôt extradé vers les États-Unis|date=2011-09-21|work=FIGARO|access-date=2017-09-09|language=fr-FR}}</ref> Horohorin was arraigned on June 7, 2012, and was detained pending trial.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/actualite-france/2011/09/21/01016-20110921ARTFIG00350-le-roi-des-hackers-bientot-extrade-vers-les-etats-unis.php|title=Le roi des hackers bientôt extradé vers les États-Unis|last=Amedeo|first=Fabrice|date=2011-09-21|work=Le Figaro|access-date=2017-04-24|language=fr-FR|issn=0182-5852}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.undernews.fr/hacking-hacktivisme/un-hacker-de-genie-extrade-vers-les-etats-unis.html|title=Un hacker de génie extradé vers les États-Unis {{!}} UnderNews|last=UnderNews|website=www.undernews.fr|language=fr|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Info.Secours/posts/416407728465737|title=Info-Secours|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.biladi.fr/091173475-badb-le-hacker-le-plus-recherche-par-la-cia-envoye-aux-etats-unis/index.html|title=BadB : Le hacker le plus recherché par la CIA envoyé aux Etats Unis|website=www.biladi.fr|language=fr|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://plus.lefigaro.fr/note/jailed-hacker-king-set-for-extradition-to-the-us-20110926-556492|title=Jailed 'Hacker King' Set For Extradition To The U.S.|work=Le Figaro.fr|access-date=2017-04-24|language=fr}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/alleged-international-credit-card-trafficker-badb-extradited-france-united-states|title=Alleged International Credit Card Trafficker "Badb" Extradited from France to the United States|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref>
The Criminal Division's Office of International Affairs handled Horohorin's extradition from France.
The case was prosecuted by attorneys Ethan Arenson (who later also prosecuted another notorious cyber criminal, [[Roman Seleznev]]), Carol Sipperly, and Corbin Weiss of the Criminal Division's Computer Crime and Intellectual Property Section ([[CCIPS]]). The District of Columbia case was investigated by the U.S. Secret Service. Assistance was provided by the [[French police|French Police Nationale Aux Frontiers]] and the Netherlands Police Agency's National Crime Squad High Tech Crime Unit. The [[FBI Atlanta Field Office]] provided information helpful to the investigation.{{cn|date=January 2018}}
The Northern District of Georgia case was prosecuted by Assistant U.S. Attorneys Nick Oldham and Lawrence R. Sommerfeld of the Northern District of Georgia, and trial attorney Sipperly of [[CCIPS]]. The Atlanta case was investigated by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]].{{cn|date=January 2018}}
Horohorin was represented by [[Arkady L. Bukh]] during proceedings in the U.S.{{cn|date=January 2018}} On October 25, 2012, Horohorin pleaded guilty to two counts of access device fraud as well as conspiracy to commit wire fraud.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/international-credit-card-trafficker-sentenced-88-months-prison|title=International Credit Card Trafficker Sentenced to 88 Months in Prison|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-10-26}}</ref>
On April 5, 2013, Horohorin was sentenced to serve 88 months in prison for his role in the theft of more than $9 million from RBS Worldpay,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bankinfosecurity.com/rbs-worldpay-hacked-15-million-cardholders-at-risk-a-1150|title=RBS WorldPay Hacked|access-date=2017-09-09|language=en}}</ref> (an Atlanta-based credit card processor), and trafficking in millions of stolen credit and debit cards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/international-credit-card-trafficker-sentenced-88-months-prison|title=International Credit Card Trafficker Sentenced to 88 Months in Prison|website=www.justice.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.securityweek.com/notorious-carder-badb-sentenced-88-months|title=Notorious Carder 'BadB' Sentenced to 88 Months {{!}} SecurityWeek.Com|website=www.securityweek.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref>
In February 2017, Horohorin was released and was deported from the United States.<ref>https://pp.userapi.com/c638131/v638131888/3bed1/3zunifG6wdU.jpg</ref>
== Post-prison activities == The U.S. assigned two [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement]] (ICE) agents to escort Horohorin, while being deported, to Israel, using U.S. airline companies only. Such measures caused Horohorin to be held for what he considered extra time in ICE custody; according to his lawyer, [[Arkady L. Bukh]], "Horohorin opposed ICE detention fiercely, refusing to stay any extra minute in US and demanding to be deported, claiming that his sentence is finished and offering to pay his own plane tickets".{{cn|date=January 2018}}
Horohorin works as private consultant and security auditor for cybersec.org<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2016/12/12/technology/russian-hackers-cybersec.cnnw/index.html|title=Russian hackers consult for this cybersecurity startup|last=Sebastian|first=Clare|date=2016-12-12|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/video/technology/2014/10/29/mind-of-a-hacker.cnnmoney/|title=In the mind of a hacker|website=CNNMoney|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wwlp.com/2016/12/10/hiring-a-russian-hacker-in-the-u-s/|title=Hiring a Russian hacker in the U.S.|last=Sebastian|first=Clare|last2=CNN|date=2016-12-10|website=WWLP.com|access-date=2017-04-24}}</ref>
